# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-league
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The **1961 Major League Baseball expansion** resulted in the formation of two new Major League Baseball (MLB) franchises in the American League (AL).
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] A new club was started in Washington, D.C., and took the existing name of the Senators, as the previous team of the same name moved to Minneapolis–Saint Paul for the start of the 1961 season and became the Minnesota Twins.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The second new franchise was granted to an ownership group led by Gene Autry for a team in Los Angeles who named themselves the Angels.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The two new teams each paid a fee of $2.1 million and became the 17th and 18th franchises in MLB.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The expansion was part of an initiative in response to the perceived threat of a proposed third major league, the Continental League.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1962, the National League (NL) also added two new teams, the Houston Colt .45s (later renamed the Astros) and the New York Mets.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] For a 50-year period from 1903 to 1952, MLB's 16-team structure remained intact.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] No franchises were relocated during this period, although five markets, Boston, Chicago, New York City, Philadelphia, and St.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] According to authors Andy McCue and Eric Thompson, "By 1953, ...
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Population had moved from the northeast quadrant to the vibrant cities of the West and South.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The situation changed as the Boston Braves moved to Milwaukee in 1953, the St.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Louis Browns relocated to Baltimore a year later, and the Philadelphia Athletics moved to Kansas City in 1955.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Then, before the 1958 season, the two New York City teams in the NL moved to the West Coast with the Dodgers moving to Los Angeles and the Giants moving to San Francisco.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] New York City sought a replacement NL franchise, and by December 1958 MLB had created an Expansion Committee.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Despite the formation of the group, MLB displayed little intention of adding a New York team.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The relocation of the Dodgers and Giants led to a proposal for a third major league: the Continental League, which would have started by 1961 with franchises in markets MLB had previously ignored.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] In addition, MLB faced pressure from the U.S.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Congress, which indicated that efforts to prevent future expansion would potentially endanger the sport's exemption from antitrust laws.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Congress voted on a bill aimed at repealing the exemption, but it failed to pass.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] However, MLB moved to expand after a rival league became a possibility.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The potential threat posed by the Continental League ended in August 1960, when the NL proposed expanding to include four of the new organization's clubs.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The AL then became interested in the idea of expansion.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Expansion Committee chairman Del Webb initially backed the addition of a Houston-based franchise, but the NL spoiled the idea when it announced the addition of teams in that city and New York for 1962.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] For many years, Los Angeles had been rumored to be a potential site for an AL franchise.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] At the time of the expansion, the Los Angeles area was the second-most populated in the U.S., and several sports teams had already moved into the city, including the NL's Dodgers.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Actor Gene Autry led a group that paid $2.1 million for the right to place an MLB team in Los Angeles.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Autry, who owned radio stations, had been seeking to acquire a contract to broadcast baseball games when he traveled to MLB's Winter Meetings.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] After the Meetings, on December 6, 1960, his group received franchise rights.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Los Angeles team was initially scheduled to begin play in 1962, but a relocation plan elsewhere in the AL resulted in the start date being moved up to 1961.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The club was nicknamed the Angels, after a Pacific Coast League team that had previously played in the city.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] To secure the name rights, Autry paid a $350,000 fee to Dodgers owner Walter O'Malley, who had purchased the minor league Angels before relocating the Dodgers to Los Angeles.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Initially, leading figures in Minneapolis–St.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Paul, Minnesota, had sought an expansion franchise.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] However, Senators owner Calvin Griffith believed his team could not prosper in the capital city of Washington, D.C., and sought to relocate to Minnesota.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Senators had played in Washington, D.C., starting in 1901, and had won the 1924 World Series.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Starting in the 1940s, however, the club had slipped towards the bottom of the AL standings for most seasons.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] In October 1960, the AL permitted the Senators to move in time for next year's season, and gave Washington, D.C., an expansion team.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The former Senators changed their name to the Minnesota Twins, and the new expansion team took the Senators name.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The decision was partially in response to pressure from Congress, which had wanted a replacement for the former Senators.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] As with the Angels' ownership group, the new Senators' owners paid a $2.1 million fee for the right to an MLB franchise.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The two new teams became the 17th and 18th clubs in MLB.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Furthermore, the American League season itself was expanded from 154 games per team to 162.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] A draft was held on December 14, 1960, to stock the new teams with players from the existing AL clubs.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] All teams were required to make seven players draftable from their regular rosters, along with eight more from their expanded rosters of 40 players, with the number of players that could be selected from one franchise capped at seven.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Angels and Senators were limited to 28 picks each, and were forced to pay $75,000 per pick.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] There were also requirements to choose certain numbers of players for each position.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Angels won the first overall pick in the expansion draft via coin toss and used it to select New York Yankees pitcher Eli Grba.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Senators followed by taking another Yankees pitcher, Bobby Shantz, with their first choice.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Angels manager Bill Rigney later said that the teams had not been notified about the rules by the AL.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Despite an effort by AL president Joe Cronin that required both teams to relinquish earlier selections and choose different players, imbalances still existed in player selections; seven of the eight AL teams had had five or more players drafted by the Angels or Senators.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] In response, player trades between the expansion teams were mandated by Cronin.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] In the last of these trades, future Cy Young Award-winning pitcher Dean Chance was sent to the Angels by Washington.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1961, Wrigley Field (unaffiliated with the stadium of the same name in Chicago), a former minor league stadium, served as the home of the Angels; for the next four seasons, they shared Dodger Stadium with the Dodgers.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Los Angeles won 70 games in its first season, exceeding expectations.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The following season, they held first place in the AL as late as July 4, ending the year with 86 victories.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] However, the team's performance declined in future years, as its strategy of acquiring "recognizable names" led to aging talent whose output fell before the Angels' minor league system could replace them.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Angels moved into Anaheim Stadium in 1966, and won their first World Series in 2002, while known as the Anaheim Angels.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Senators experienced a lack of strong fan interest in their inaugural season, drawing under 600,000 fans for the year.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team annually posted about 90 defeats in most future years, and did not win more games than it lost until 1969, when Washington ended the season with an 86–76 win–loss record.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The original owner of the club left early in the Senators' existence, and a second shift occurred shortly after stockbrokers James Johnson and James Lemon purchased the team from Elwood Quesada.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] In September 1971, then-owner Bob Short announced that the Senators would move to the Dallas area after the season; the team's last game in Washington was forfeited due to "unruly behavior" by Senators fans.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] It would not be until 2005 when MLB returned to Washington by relocating the NL's Montreal Expos, established in 1969, and renaming them the Washington Nationals.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Nationals would win their first World Series in 2019, while the Texas Rangers would claim their first Series win in 2023.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The 1961 expansion was the first in a series of moves that resulted in MLB nearly doubling in size to 30 franchises.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] As part of MLB's effort to prevent the formation of the Continental League, the NL added the New York Mets and Houston Colt .45s (who later changed their nickname to the Astros) for the 1962 season.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Another expansion draft was made to stock the new teams for the 1962 season.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Four new clubs joined the AL and NL in 1969, in San Diego, Kansas City, Montreal, and Seattle (although the team moved to Milwaukee the following year).
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Further two-team expansions took place in 1977, 1993, and 1998.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] The expansions had the effect of placing MLB teams across the continent; before 1961, only four teams (the Dodgers, Giants, Kansas City Athletics, and St.
[src:american-league/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion] Louis Cardinals) were based west of the Mississippi.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The **1962 Major League Baseball expansion** was the formation of two new Major League Baseball (MLB) teams for the 1962 season.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Houston Colt .45s (later renamed the Astros) and the New York Mets were added to the National League (NL), becoming the 19th and 20th teams in MLB's two leagues.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Colt .45s were the first major league team in Houston while the Mets filled the void left when the New York Giants and Brooklyn Dodgers of the NL moved to California after the 1957 season.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The expansion was the second part of an initiative that resulted in the addition of four clubs to MLB.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The previous year the American League had added the Los Angeles Angels and second incarnation of the Washington Senators.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] For a 50-year period from 1903 to 1952, MLB's 16-team structure (split into the American and National Leagues) remained intact.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] No franchises were relocated during this period, and five markets—Boston, Chicago, New York City, Philadelphia, and St.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] According to authors Andy McCue and Eric Thompson, "The less financially successful clubs in two-team cities were finding it increasingly difficult to compete" by the early 1950s.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] In addition, population changes in the United States were leading to many citizens moving away from the Northeast, where many MLB teams were based, to southern and western locations.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] From 1953 to 1955, three franchises were relocated, all of which had been in markets with two or more teams.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Prior to the 1958 season, the two New York City teams in the NL, the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Giants, moved westward; the Dodgers relocated to Los Angeles, while San Francisco became the new home of the Giants.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The city had beaten MLB to planning for future expansion, with the formation of the Mayor's Committee shortly after the Dodgers and Giants announced their moves; the committee was headed by lawyer William Shea.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] In addition, MLB was facing pressure from the U.S.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Congress, which indicated that efforts to prevent future expansion would arouse interest in weakening the sport's exemption from antitrust laws.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Congress voted on a bill aimed at repealing the exemption, but it failed.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] MLB formed an expansion committee, which voted in favor of adding four new teams, two in each league, by 1961–62.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] MLB sought cities that had received interest from the Continental League.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Among them were Houston, Los Angeles, New York City, and Washington, D.C.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The NL announced an expansion as the 1960 World Series was in progress, with new teams in Houston and New York City.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Shea had been a supporter of the Continental League concept, and had attracted several investors.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] A potential Houston team also had numerous partners, many of whom had oil interests.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The AL initially showed interest in adding a Houston team, but the investors wanted an NL franchise.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] MLB granted the two cities franchises on October 17, 1960.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Furthermore, the National League season itself was expanded from 154 games (per team) to 162.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The idea of a replacement NL club in New York City was strongly supported by city Mayor Robert Wagner.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The city was unable to secure funding for a proposed Flushing Meadows stadium in time for play in 1962, so the Mets played at the Polo Grounds, the previous home of the New York Giants.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] George Weiss was the president of the team, and seven-time World Series championship-winning manager Casey Stengel was hired to lead the Mets on the field.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Houston Sports Association was formed in 1957 and bought a minor league baseball team four years later.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The group was given a controlling interest in Houston's expansion team, which was nicknamed the Colt .45s.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] A draft was held on October 10, 1961, to stock the new teams with players from the existing NL clubs.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] All eight original NL teams were required to make 15 players available to be drafted by the Colt .45s and Mets from their regular rosters.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] A maximum number of possible selections in the draft was set at 45.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The players were divided into three price classes, based on what would be charged to the expansion teams.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] They could each take 4 "premium" players, who cost $125,000 per player, 16 $75,000 players, and 3 $50,000 players; the Mets chose only 2 $50,000 players.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] A coin toss was held to determine who would receive the first overall pick in the expansion draft; it was won by Houston.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Colt .45s had the first overall pick in the expansion draft and selected San Francisco Giants infielder Eddie Bressoud.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Mets' first selection was another player from the Giants, catcher Hobie Landrith.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Mets' later selections in the draft included Gil Hodges of the Los Angeles Dodgers and Don Zimmer of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The teams alternated choices through the first 36 picks, before the Colt .45s selected Jim Golden and Joey Amalfitano consecutively.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Each team then had every other selection until the end of the draft, which came after the Mets picked Lee Walls of the Philadelphia Phillies with the 45th overall choice.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Both teams selected five outfielders in the expansion draft.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Colt .45s picked seven infielders, one more than the Mets; New York's three catchers chosen was one more than the two taken by Houston.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Seven pitchers were taken by the Mets; the Colt .45s took four.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] After losses in nine straight games to start the 1962 season, the Mets set a then-MLB record with 120 losses in their 160 games played.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team featured two pitchers who lost at least 20 games and had the lowest batting average in the NL.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Despite the repeated setbacks on the field, the Mets proved popular with fans of the previous NL franchises in New York, drawing more than 900,000 fans to the Polo Grounds in 1962.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Mets played one more season at the stadium, before Shea Stadium was built in time for the 1964 season, in which New York drew 1.8 million spectators.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] By 1969, the Mets had won their first World Series, one of two earned by the franchise.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] In addition, New York has won five NL pennants and six division titles.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Colt .45s played their first three seasons at Colt Stadium before beginning play at the Astrodome in 1965.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team won its first game, defeating the Chicago Cubs by a score of 11–2.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] At the end of their first season, the Colt .45s were in eighth place in the NL; the Cubs and Mets were behind them.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The franchise did not finish higher than eighth over the next six years, before improving in the following decade.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Houston eventually changed their team nickname to the Astros, and won the 2005 NL pennant; in addition, they played in the National League Championship Series three other times.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Astros moved to the American League in the 2013 season.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] They made their second World Series appearance four years later, winning for the first time.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Astros would win two more AL pennants, in 2019 and 2021, before winning a second World Series title in 2022.
[src:american-league/1962-major-league-baseball-expansion] Following the 1961 expansion that resulted in the addition of the Los Angeles Angels and the second incarnation of the Washington Senators to the AL, the 1962 expansion was part of a series of moves that led to MLB nearly doubling in size to 30 franchises.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The **1969 Major League Baseball expansion** resulted in the establishment of expansion franchises in Kansas City and Seattle in the American League and in Montreal and San Diego in the National League of Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Kansas City Royals, Montreal Expos, San Diego Padres, and the Seattle Pilots began play in the 1969 season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] One of the reasons for expansion was increasing pressure to maintain the sport as the US national pastime, particularly because of the increasing popularity of professional football.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] As a result of expansion, the American and National Leagues reorganized.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Each league was split into two divisions, forming the American League East, American League West, National League East, and National League West.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Other candidate cities that were considered in 1967 included Buffalo, Dallas–Fort Worth, and Milwaukee.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The latter two were rejected because they were close to cities that already had an MLB team (Houston and Chicago, respectively).
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] By August, MLB had plans to expand to two 12-team leagues by 1970, and had squelched the possibility of a third league, such as the Continental League proposed in 1959 or the proposal made in August 1968 by Ron Plaza consisting of an Eastern, Central, and Western League.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1960, the American League conducted a survey to determine potential expansion cities.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The list included Atlanta, Buffalo, Dallas–Fort Worth, Denver, Oakland, San Diego, Seattle, and Toronto.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Kansas City had been the home to the Kansas City Athletics from 1955, when the team moved from Philadelphia, to 1967, after which the team moved to Oakland.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] A committee of American League owners denied his requests.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] In October 1967, with the team's lease at Municipal Stadium expired, Finley once again proposed to move the franchise to Oakland, this time at the owners' meetings in Chicago.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] During the first ballot of the committee of American League owners on October 18, he received six supporting votes, one opposing vote (from the Baltimore Orioles), and the Cleveland Indians, New York Yankees, and Washington Senators abstained from voting.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] American League president Joe Cronin requested a second ballot, in which the New York Yankees were the only team to change their status, opting to support the move and giving Finley "the seven votes necessary to move the team".
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] In a press release, Cronin announced the move and promised to expand the league by two more clubs no later than 1971.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Oakland Athletics began play in the 1968 Major League Baseball season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Cronin conveyed the news to Kansas City mayor Ilus Davis and Stuart Symington, a US Senator from Missouri.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Cronin had thought that the compromise to install a new team by 1971 would be acceptable to them as compensation for the loss of the Athletics.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Instead, Symington threatened to challenge Major League Baseball's antitrust exemption with federal legislation, and to also challenge the reserve clause.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Davis threatened a lawsuit to block the move.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Tom Yawkey arranged a meeting of the owners still at the convention, during which the league agreed to accelerate the expansion process and assured that Kansas City would be granted a new franchise to begin play no later than the 1969 season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] This would require another franchise to be established at the same time to ensure the league had an even number of teams for a balanced schedule.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] On the floor of the United States Senate on October 19, Symington described Finley as "one of the most disreputable characters ever to enter the American sports scene" and said that "Oakland is the luckiest city since Hiroshima".
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Ewing Kauffman won rights to the franchise, and paid a $5.5 million expansion fee for the Royals, which played games at Municipal Stadium until the end of the 1972 season, after which the team moved to Royals Stadium, now known as Kauffman Stadium.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] By the 1960s, with Seattle's population growing, the city became the largest to host a Pacific Coast League team, the Seattle Rainiers.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The league's stature also declined with the move of the Brooklyn Dodgers to Los Angeles and the New York Giants to San Francisco, which caused those cities' PCL teams to relocate to much smaller markets.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1964, the city purchased Sick's Stadium for $1.1 million.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1965, the Rainiers were sold to the Los Angeles Angels, who renamed the team the *Seattle Angels*.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The city made several attempts to lure a Major League Baseball team.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Daley visited the city when searching for a new home for the Cleveland Indians.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] He was unimpressed with the stadium, citing it as the primary reason to terminate his quest to move his team.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Charlie Finley also found the stadium inadequate during a 1967 visit, and so rejected Seattle as a potential target for moving the Kansas City Athletics.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Because of this, the city instead tried to lobby for an expansion franchise at the 1967 owners' meetings in Chicago.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The delegation also had support from two US Senators, Henry M.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Jackson and Warren Magnuson, the latter of whom was the chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, a committee which has "jurisdiction over the major league's business activities".
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Coupled with Symington's threats related to the move of the Kansas City Athletics, the political influence swayed the American League owners.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] However, they were reluctant to expand in 1969 without a Seattle stadium bond issue.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Seattle delegation assured the owners that Sick's Stadium could be renovated in five months to fulfill the minimum requirements until a new stadium was built; with this, the owners agreed to a 1969 expansion, and approved teams in Kansas City and Seattle.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] On December 1, 1967 at the Winter Meetings in Mexico City, the franchise was officially awarded to Pacific Northwest Sports, which received $5.5 million in funding from Daley, who thus had 47% ownership of the venture.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Other owners included Max and Dewey Soriano.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The award was contingent on renovation of Sick's Stadium to increase its seating capacity from 11,000 to 30,000 by the start of the 1969 season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Sorianos persuaded notable athletes to advocate for the $40 million King County stadium bond issue, including baseball players Mickey Mantle, Carl Yastrzemski, and Joe DiMaggio, and football player Y.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Tittle; the bond issue was approved by 62.3% of the electorate.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The National League had received applications for an expansion franchise from Buffalo, Dallas–Fort Worth, Milwaukee, Montreal, San Diego, and Toronto as well as an informal bid from Denver.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Montreal had a long history of interest in baseball.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The sport became increasingly popular in eastern North America in the 1850s and 1860s, and Montreal "became a special hotbed", so much so that by the early 1860s Montreal authorities banned play in city parks and streets for public safety.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Minor league baseball became a presence in the city.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1946, the Montreal Royals, a Triple-A team affiliated with the Brooklyn Dodgers of Major League Baseball, became the first team having any affiliation to MLB to break baseball's color barrier.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Jackie Robinson, who had been signed to a contract by Branch Rickey in late 1945, played the entire season for the International League team.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] He and teammates Roy Partlow and Johnny Wright were the first black players in the league since the 1880s.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The next year, Robinson became the first black player to play for a Major League Baseball team.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1951 in Farnham, a town east of Montreal, Sam Bankhead became the first black manager in Minor League Baseball; he was a player-manager for the Farnham Pirates of the Provincial League that year.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Montreal City Councilor Gerry Snyder spoke to Ford C.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Frick sometime after the 1962 Major League Baseball expansion, during which he was told Montreal would not receive an expansion franchise unless it had a stadium in which to contest matches.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] At the Winter Meetings in Mexico City on December 2, 1967, Snyder presented a proposal to Major League Baseball owners to establish a franchise in the city.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Several influential owners pledged their support for a Montreal franchise in that meeting, including Walter O'Malley, Roy Hofheinz, and John Galbreath.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Certain that Hofheinz would object to a Dallas–Fort Worth bid and that the San Diego bid was near certain to be successful, Snyder deemed a bid from Buffalo to be the strongest bid against which to compete.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] On May 27, 1968, the National League officially awarded a franchise to Montreal to commence play in the 1969 season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] National League president Warren Giles had encouraged the owners during the meeting, stating "If we're going to expand, let's really spread it out".
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Montreal Expos became the first franchise to be awarded to a city outside the United States.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Congress, members collectively condemned the decision.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Because of the slow pace of progress in meeting commitments, Jean-Louis Lévesque withdrew his financial support in the franchise on July 31, 1968.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Snyder quickly found another investor, Charles Bronfman, and the team met the deadline of 15 August for the initial $1.1 million installment, before which Jarry Park was selected as the team's stadium for the short term.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Renovations to the park were made by adding uncovered bleacher seats along the right and left field lines, and an electronic scoreboard installed beyond right field.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team had some issues committing to a new stadium, as required by the franchise award, and it was said that the team had agreed to build a dome at the Autostade and use it as their stadium if a new stadium was not built by 1970.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] It had originally intended to lease the stadium and expand its seating capacity from 26,000 to 37,000, but then chose Jarry Park instead.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The ownership group paid $12.5 million for the team.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] John McHale was hired as the team's first president, and Jim Fanning its first general manager.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Many names had been considered for the team, including *Royals* which had a strong association with the city, but the name had already been adopted by the new Kansas City franchise.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] After rejecting various options, including "Voyageurs" and "Nationals", the name *Expos* was chosen in honour of Expo 67 and because it was the same in both of the city's official languages.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] McHale stated that the name would "help Montreal be identified properly as the city that gave the world Expo 67".
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Arnholt Smith, owner of the PCL San Diego Padres (PCL), won a bid for an expansion team in the National League for the 1969 season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] On May 27, 1968, the National League officially awarded a franchise to San Diego to commence play in the 1969 season for a fee of $12.5 million for the team.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] After the 1968 PCL season, Smith surrendered the franchise, which moved to Eugene, Oregon, and transferred the Padre name to his new NL team, the San Diego Padres.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Eddie Leishman was named general manager of the MLB Padres, with club president and minority investor Buzzie Bavasi, formerly GM of the Los Angeles Dodgers (having resigned to take the new role), playing a dominant role in its baseball operations as president of the team.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] In order to stock the roster of each team, a draft was held in which each of the extant teams would make available to the expansion franchises some of the players on their major league and minor league rosters.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Each expansion team selected 30 players in the draft, and each of the extant teams lost six players.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The extant teams were allowed to protect 15 players in their organization from the draft.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] After each player lost, another three players could be protected.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The extant teams were not informed of the draft selections of the expansion teams until the draft was complete.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] On October 14, 1968, the Montreal Expos and San Diego Padres drafted players exclusively from National League teams.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The draft was conducted from the Windsor Hotel in Montreal, in which four rooms were reserved: one for the Expos, one for the Padres, one for the remaining 10 teams, and one in which draft selections were made.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Padres won a coin flip, and so had the first selection, which they used to draft Ollie Brown from the San Francisco Giants.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Montreal's first selection was Pittsburgh Pirates utility player Manny Mota.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Selections were made by general manager Jim Fanning and manager Gene Mauch for Montreal, and general manager Buzzie Bavasi and manager Preston Gómez for San Diego.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] On October 15, the Kansas City Royals and Seattle Pilots drafted players exclusively from American League teams.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The draft was conducted in Boston, at the Sheraton Hotel.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Because Buffalo was not awarded an expansion franchise, Erie County legislators reconsidered a $50 million bond issue that was to be used for the construction of a domed stadium for baseball and football.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The applicants that submitted a bid for Dallas–Fort Worth claimed that Roy Hofheinz, owner of the Houston Astros, had blocked their bid in order to preserve Houston's radio and television broadcast revenue.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Chicago White Sox owner Arthur Allyn, Jr. complained about his team being in the same division as two expansion franchises.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The addition of four teams resulted in the reconfiguration of the leagues; each was split into an east and a west division.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The National League originally resisted a divisional split, with its president Warren Giles citing "the tradition and history of baseball".
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] By July 10, the National League owners had agreed to a divisional split, in which the National League East would consist of the Chicago Cubs, Montreal Expos, New York Mets, Philadelphia Phillies, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Louis Cardinals, and the National League West would consist of the Atlanta Braves, Cincinnati Reds, Houston Astros, Los Angeles Dodgers, San Diego Padres, and San Francisco Giants.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Game scheduling issues had to be resolved; league-wide, there would be 1,944 games compared to 1,620 for the 1968 Major League Baseball season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The American League had considered decreasing the number of games played by each team to 152 or 156 from 162 that had been played each season since 1961, and the National League either 162 or 165 games, but the leagues agreed to a 162-game schedule in a meeting on 10 July 1968.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Each team would play 18 games against every other team in their own division, and 12 games against each league opponent in the other division.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] A best-of-five post-season playoff series between league division winners was also introduced.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Kansas City Royals have been the most successful of the four 1969 expansion teams.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The franchise fielded competitive teams in the 1970s and 1980s and won the 1985 World Series.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] After a 29-year postseason drought, the Royals returned to postseason play in the 2014 season, before winning their second World Series title in 2015.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The San Diego Padres had nine consecutive losing seasons, and have since made the playoffs seven times.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] A potential sale and relocation to Washington for the 1974 season was averted when, while the sale was tied up in legal action, Ray Kroc (who had just retired from his position as McDonald's CEO) bought the team and kept them in San Diego.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Padres twice made the World Series in 1984 and 1998, but lost both appearances.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Montreal Expos had good attendance for the 1969 season, and after having losing records for ten years, were competitive in the 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Its 1994 season put it in first place before the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike prematurely ended the season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team's fortunes declined thereafter, and the team moved to Washington, D.C. for the 2005 season, becoming the Washington Nationals.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The franchise won its first playoff series in 1981 when the Expos defeated the Phillies in the NLDS, after a split-season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] As the Nationals, the franchise won the NLDS in 2019, over the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Louis Cardinals in their first ever NLCS, and defeat the Houston Astros (moved to the AL prior to the 2013 season) to win the franchise's first World Series title.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Seattle Pilots fared the worst of the four expansion franchises, playing only in the 1969 season.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team performed poorly on the field, and faced financial difficulties owing to no television coverage, a stadium with problems, and the highest ticket and concession prices in the league.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Owners of other American League teams wanted Soriano and Daley to sell the team to a Seattle owner who would improve the team and address issues at Sick's Stadium, particularly uncovered seats with bad views.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] After several attempts to sell the team to a Seattle owner failed, on April 1, 1970, Judge Sidney Volinn declared the team officially bankrupt; it was sold to Bud Selig, who moved the team to Milwaukee and renamed it the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] Selig had negotiated a deal for the purchase with Soriano during Game 1 of the 1969 World Series.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] As a result of the relocation, in 1970 the city of Seattle, King County, and the state of Washington sued the American League for breach of contract.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] The $32.5 million lawsuit was settled in 1976 when the American League offered the city a franchise in exchange for termination of the lawsuit.
[src:american-league/1969-major-league-baseball-expansion] This led to the establishment of the Seattle Mariners via the 1977 Major League Baseball expansion.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The **1977 Major League Baseball expansion** resulted in the establishment of expansion franchises in Seattle and Toronto in the American League of Major League Baseball.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Seattle Mariners and Toronto Blue Jays began play in the 1977 season, becoming the 25th and 26th teams in Major League Baseball.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Seattle and Toronto were included in a list of potential expansion cities in a survey conducted by the American League in 1960.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Seattle Pilots only played one season, during which they faced financial difficulties stemming from a complete lack of television coverage, a poorly performing team, a stadium with problems, and the highest ticket and concession prices in the league.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Owners of other American League teams wanted Dewey Soriano and William R.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Daley to sell the team to a Seattle owner who would improve the team and address issues at Sick's Stadium, particularly uncovered seats with bad views.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] As a result of the relocation of the Seattle Pilots to Milwaukee, in 1970 the city of Seattle, King County and the state of Washington sued the American League for breach of contract.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The $32.5 million lawsuit proceeded until 1976, when at trial the American League offered the city a franchise in exchange for the city, county, and state to drop the suit.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] On November 2, 1972, King County had broken ground on the Kingdome, which would come to be used by the Seattle Mariners for baseball and by the Seahawks for football.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] On January 15, 1976, the expansion franchise was approved, becoming the 13th franchise in the American League.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] It was owned by Lester Smith and Danny Kaye, who paid an expansion fee of US$6.5 million.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Owing to the history surrounding the franchise, sportswriter Emmett Watson of the Seattle Post-Intelligencer joked that the team should be named the *Seattle Litigants*.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Toronto had a long history of interest in baseball.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Its first professional baseball team was established in 1885, and in 1886 Sunlight Park was built to host its games.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1897, Hanlan's Point Stadium was built at the Toronto Islands for the Toronto Maple Leafs of the International League, and on September 5, 1914 it was the site of baseball legend Babe Ruth's first professional home run and only minor league home run.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1926, Maple Leaf Stadium was built for the Toronto Maple Leafs.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team was successful, sometimes drawing more fans than established Major League Baseball teams.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team was owned by Jack Kent Cooke, who in the mid-1950s sought municipal financing of a major league baseball park on the grounds of the Canadian National Exhibition.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] He was also involved in the failed attempt to establish the Continental League as a third league in Major League Baseball in the early 1960s.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Maple Leaf Stadium was demolished in 1968 after the Toronto Maple Leafs were sold to Walter Dilbeck and moved to Louisville, Kentucky.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In the early 1970s, Toronto City Council alderman Paul Godfrey proposed a plan for a publicly financed domed stadium in the city, but it was opposed by taxpayers and amateur sports groups.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Undeterred, he proposed renovation of Exhibition Stadium to support baseball.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The stadium was renovated in anticipation of the city being awarded a Major League Baseball team, costing CA$15 million.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Half of the funds were provided by the municipal government, and the other half from an interest-free loan from the provincial Government of Ontario.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Its seating capacity was increased to 40,000.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] There had been strong interest from several groups and individuals to own a Major League Baseball team in the city.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The most prominent was Labatt Brewing Company, who wanted to use ownership of a sports team as a means to establish a visible presence in the Toronto market.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Giants had failed to repay a US$500,000 loan from Major League Baseball, and had experienced declining revenues since the relocation of the Kansas City Athletics to Oakland in 1968.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Of the sale price, US$5,250,000 was to be placed in escrow to "meet certain possible obligations with respect to the transaction", especially the lease of Candlestick Park, which would expire in 1994.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The new owners of the Giants, led by Don McDougall, would move the team to Toronto pending approval from the other eleven National League teams, which would be sought on January 14 at the Winter Meetings of General managers in Phoenix.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team would be known as the Toronto Giants and would begin play during the 1976 Major League Baseball season.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The deal was scuttled by a Superior Court of California, which issued an injunction blocking the sale on February 11, 1976; the injunction was requested by the city of San Francisco on January 10.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The National Exhibition Company eventually accepted a purchase proposal from Bob Lurie in a deal brokered by George Moscone, the Mayor of San Francisco; Lurie elected to keep the team in San Francisco.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] This was the third scuttled attempt by Labatt to bring an MLB team to Toronto, after failures to acquire the Baltimore Orioles and the Cleveland Indians.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Soon after, Godfrey received a phone call from Kansas City Royals owner Ewing Kauffman informing him that he supported a Toronto franchise for the American League.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] During an owners meeting held on March 20, 1976, the American League franchises voted 11-1 to expand the league with a Toronto franchise, to which National League owners resolved to consider a Toronto franchise to begin play in the 1977 season.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Bowie Kuhn, at the time the Commissioner of Baseball, planned for the National League to expand with new franchises in Toronto and Washington, D.C., and for the American League to add a new franchise in New Orleans in addition to the already-awarded Seattle franchise.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] On March 29, National League owners met and voted in favour of the expansion plans, but they were rejected because the vote was not unanimous, with dissenting votes from the owners of the Cincinnati Reds and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] A subsequent vote on April 26 ended this plan with a 7–5 result in favour of the proposal, again failing to achieve unanimity.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Two groups bid for the rights to franchise ownership in the city, which presented bids during an American League owner's meeting on March 26, 1976.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Ultimately, an ownership group named Metro Baseball Ltd. consisting of Labatt Brewing Company, the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, and Imperial Trust won the bid for a franchise fee of CA$7 million.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The other bid was made by Atlantic Packaging.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The winning bid was represented by legal counsel Herb Solway and Gord Kirke.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Kirke prepared the original documents which led to the foundation of the team in 1976.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] After the city was awarded the franchise, U.S.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] President Gerald Ford attempted to pressure Major League Baseball to instead award the franchise to Washington, D.C., which he claimed should have a team before Toronto.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Both the American League and National League dismissed his request.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1974, the Toronto City Council approved a further CA$2.8 million for renovations to Exhibition Stadium, retrofitting the stadium for baseball and would be ready in time for the 1977 season.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Paul Beeston was hired as the team's first employee on May 10, 1976, and Peter Bavasi was hired as the team's first president and general manager on June 18, 1976.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In order to stock the roster of each team, a draft was held on November 5, 1976 in which each of the extant teams would make available to the expansion franchises some of the players on their major league and minor league rosters.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Each team was allowed to protect fifteen players on the major league roster, and an additional three players after each of the first and second round of the draft.
[src:american-league/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Seattle Mariners and Toronto Blue Jays each selected 30 players in the draft.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The **1993 Major League Baseball expansion** resulted in Major League Baseball (MLB) adding two expansion teams to the National League (NL) for the 1993 season: the Colorado Rockies and the Florida Marlins (now known as the Miami Marlins).
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Talks of expansion began on August 8, 1985, when the players and the owners agreed to a new collective bargaining agreement (CBA).
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The basic agreement allowed the National League to expand by two members to match the American League, which had done so in 1977.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Details of expansion were finalized in the 1990 CBA.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Ten cities were considered serious candidates for the two spots: Buffalo, Charlotte, Denver, Miami, Nashville, Orlando, Phoenix, Sacramento, Tampa Bay, and Washington.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Petersburg and Pilot Field in Buffalo were built specifically to lure an existing or expansion MLB franchise.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The National League expansion committee consisted of Pittsburgh Pirates Chairman Doug Danfort, New York Mets president Fred Wilpon and Houston Astros owner John McMullen.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] On December 18, 1990, the committee eliminated Charlotte, Nashville, Phoenix and Sacramento from consideration to cut the list down to six finalists.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] With three sites from Florida remaining in contention it became apparent that one would win out while the other spot would go to a non-Florida team.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] After previous failed attempts to bring Major League Baseball to the state of Colorado (most notably the Pittsburgh Pirates nearly relocating to Denver following the Pittsburgh drug trials in 1985), by the late 1980s a team seemed to be a possibility in Denver.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Eugene Orza, associate general counsel of the Major League Baseball Players Association, stated that he expected Denver would receive one of the expansion franchises.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Colorado Baseball Commission, led by banking executive Larry Varnell, was successful in getting Denver voters to approve a 0.1% sales tax to help finance a new baseball stadium.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Also, an advisory committee was formed in 1990 by then-Governor of Colorado Roy Romer to recruit an ownership group.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The group selected was led by John Antonucci, an Ohio beverage distributor, and Michael I.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Monus, the head of the Phar-Mor drugstore chain.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Local and regional companies—such as Erie Lake, Hensel Phelps Construction, KOA Radio, and the *Rocky Mountain News*—rounded out the group.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Denver group chose to call their franchise the Colorado Rockies, the same name used as the National Hockey League franchise that played in Denver from 1976 to 1982.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Senator Connie Mack III from Florida, the grandson of baseball great Connie Mack and a member of the Senate Task Force on Major League Baseball, pushed Baseball Commissioner Fay Vincent to expand to Florida.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] On March 7, 1990, Wayne Huizenga, CEO of Blockbuster Entertainment Corporation, announced he had purchased 15% of the NFL's Miami Dolphins and 50% of the Dolphins' home, Joe Robbie Stadium, for an estimated $30 million.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Huizenga stated his intention to aggressively pursue an expansion franchise.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] MLB had announced a few months earlier that it intended to add two new teams to the National League.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] It was a foregone conclusion that one of them would be placed in Florida; the only question was whether Huizenga would beat out competing groups from Orlando and Tampa Bay.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Orlando fielded a very spirited campaign bolstered by its family-oriented tourism industry.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Tampa Bay already had a baseball park — the Florida Suncoast Dome in St.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] On June 10, 1990, Huizenga was awarded an expansion franchise in the National League (NL) for a $95 million expansion fee and the team began operations in 1993 as the Florida Marlins.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] In June 1991, the expansion committee accepted the bids of the Miami and Denver groups to debut in 1993.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Expansion was approved unanimously by all teams in July 1991.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] An expansion draft to stock both franchises was set for November 1992.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Though previous expansions allowed the drafting of players from the same league only, Vincent declared that the American League would receive $42 million of the National League's $190 million in expansion revenue so that the AL would provide players in the National League expansion draft.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] In an attempt to win support in the American League and balance the vote, Vincent decreed that the AL owners were entitled to 22% of the $190 million take.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] This decision marked the first time in expansion history that leagues were required to share expansion revenue or provide players for another league's expansion draft.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Vincent said the owners expanded to raise money to pay their collusion debt.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Tampa Bay Baseball Group sued MLB for allegedly reneging on an agreement to grant an expansion team to Tampa.
[src:american-league/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The suit was settled in 2003, five years after Tampa's major league team, the Devil Rays (now simply the Rays), began play in the American League.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The **1994–95 Major League Baseball strike** was the eighth and longest work stoppage in Major League Baseball (MLB) history, as well as the fourth in-season work stoppage in 22 years.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike began on August 12, 1994, and resulted in the remainder of that season, including the postseason and the World Series, being canceled.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This was the first time in ninety years, since 1904, that a World Series was not played.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike was suspended on April 2, 1995, after 232 days, making it the longest such stoppage in MLB history and the longest work stoppage in a major professional sports league at the time (breaking the record set by the 1981 strike, also in MLB).
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] As a result of the strike, a total of 948 games were canceled.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Both the 1994 and 1995 seasons were not played to a complete 162 games; the strike began after the teams had played at least 113 games in 1994.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Each team played a total of 144 games in 1995.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This was the first time in North American professional sports that an entire postseason was canceled because of labor disputes; the second (and most recent) was the cancellation of the National Hockey League's 2005 Stanley Cup playoffs as a result of the entire 2004–05 season being canceled.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Coincidentally, the NHL also experienced a labor dispute of their own in 1994.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In response to a worsening financial situation in baseball, the owners of Major League Baseball teams collectively proposed a salary cap to their players.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Ownership claimed that small-market clubs would fall by the wayside unless teams agreed to share local broadcasting revenues (to increase equity among the teams) and enact a salary cap, a proposal that the players adamantly opposed.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On January 18, 1994, the owners approved a new revenue-sharing plan keyed to a salary cap, which required the players' approval.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The following day, the owners amended the Major League agreement by giving complete power to the commissioner on labor negotiations.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The dispute was played out with a backdrop of years of hostility and mistrust between the two sides.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] What arguably stood in the way of a compromise settlement was the absence of an official commissioner ever since the owners forced Fay Vincent to resign in September 1992.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This reduced trust between players and owners.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Owner representative Richard Ravitch officially unveiled the ownership proposal on June 14, 1994.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The proposal would guarantee a record $1 billion in salary and benefits.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] But the ownership proposal also would have forced clubs to fit their payrolls into a more evenly based structure.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Salary arbitration would have been eliminated, free agency would begin after four years rather than six, and owners would have retained the right to keep a four- or five-year player by matching his best offer.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Owners claimed that their proposal would raise average salaries from $1.2 million in 1994 to $2.6 million by 2001.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Fehr rejected the offer from the owners on July 18.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] He believed a salary cap was simply a way for owners to clean up their own disparity problems with no benefit to the players.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On July 13, Fehr said if serious negotiations between the players and the owners did not begin soon, the players could go out on strike in September of that year, threatening the postseason.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On December 31, 1993, Major League Baseball's collective bargaining agreement ran out with no new agreement yet signed.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] As negotiations continued to heat up, the owners decided to withhold $7.8 million that they were required to pay per previous agreement into the players' pension and benefit plans.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The final straw came on June 23 when the Senate Judiciary Committee failed to approve an antitrust legislation by a vote of 10–7.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] According to Fehr, the action left the players with little choice but to strike.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] "We felt in '94 we were pushed into it," he said.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On July 28, the Players Association executive board set August 12, 1994, as a strike date.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] When that day came, the players went ahead with their threat to walk off the job.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The last games of that baseball season were played on August 11, 1994.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On August 31, three-and-a-half hours of negotiations with federal mediators produced no progress in the strike, and no further talks were scheduled as the strike went into its 4th week.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] According to then-acting commissioner Bud Selig, September 9 was the tentative deadline for canceling the rest of the season if no agreement was reached between the owners and players.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The MLBPA offered a counterproposal to ownership on September 8 calling for a two-percent tax on the 16 franchises with the highest payrolls to be divided among the other 12 clubs.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Teams in both leagues would share 25% of all gate receipts under the MLBPA's plan.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The owners responded by claiming that the measures wouldn't meet the cost.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The rest of the season, including the World Series, was called off by Selig on September 14.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Selig acknowledged that the strike had torn an irreparable hole in the game's fabric.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The move to cancel the rest of the season meant the loss of $580 million in ownership revenue and $230 million in player salaries.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In 1994, the average MLB salary was an estimated $1.2 million.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Montreal Expos were enjoying the best season in their history at the time of the strike.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Expos had the best record in baseball, 74–40, and were six games ahead of the Atlanta Braves in the NL East despite having the second-lowest payroll in MLB.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Most baseball writers considered the Expos to be World Series contenders.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Coincidentally, the only time that the Expos had made it to the postseason was in 1981, the last time that there was a significant players' strike in Major League Baseball.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] That year, Montreal had qualified by winning the second half of the season.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike also cost Matt Williams of the San Francisco Giants a chance to beat Roger Maris' single season home run record.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] When the strike forced the cancellation of the remaining 47 games of the season, Williams had already hit 43 home runs, on pace to match Maris' single season record of 61 home runs.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Cleveland Indians second baseman Carlos Baerga was unable to extend his record two-year streak of 20 home runs, 200 hits, and 100 RBIs by a second baseman because of the strike.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] By the third day of the strike, Cleveland Indians owner Richard Jacobs directed that all souvenirs being sold at the Indians' gift shop carrying the words "inaugural season at Jacobs Field" be sold at half price.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Colorado Rockies were completing their last season at Mile High Stadium with an attendance of 3,281,511 through 57 home games for an average of 57,570 per game.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] At that pace, the team would have had a good chance of drawing over 4.6 million fans in their 81 home games if the season had continued.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This would have eclipsed the major league season attendance record of 4,483,350 fans set by the Rockies only the season before.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike meant that fans would not witness what was described as "one of the worst division races in history." The Texas Rangers were leading the newly reformed AL West despite being 10 games under .500.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The last-place California Angels were only 5+1⁄2 games out despite having the second-worst record in the majors at 21 games under .500—on pace for 96 losses.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In fact, the two last place teams in the other American League divisions (namely, the Detroit Tigers of the AL East and Milwaukee Brewers of the AL Central) had better records than the Rangers.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The National League's MVP award was given to Jeff Bagwell.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] His hand was broken by a pitch on August 10, just before the players' strike began; had the season continued, he would likely have missed the remainder of the year and might not have won the MVP.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] But because of the timing of his "lucky break", Bagwell became just the fourth player in National League history to win the award unanimously.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike caused a transaction to take an absurd turn.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Minnesota Twins traded Dave Winfield to the Cleveland Indians for a player to be named later.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Since the strike led to the season being canceled, no further transactions could be made until it was settled.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Twins would officially be listed as having sold Winfield to the Indians, but the actual transaction was conducted much differently.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Instead of the Indians buying the contract outright, team management went out for a meal with Twins management and the Indians paid the tab; this essentially meant that Winfield had been traded for dinner.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Arguably, the biggest storyline of the strike was the New York Yankees.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Yankees had not been in the postseason since 1981.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Because the Yankees' prior postseason chances had also been cut short by a strike, news media reported on the parallels between the two Yankee teams (1981 and 1994), both of which had division leads taken away by strike actions.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] MLB Baseball would not attempt another salary cap until the 2026 season.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On December 5, it was announced Richard Ravitch would step down as negotiator for the owners on December 31, 1994.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Ravitch instead resigned on December 6, 1994.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On December 14, labor talks headed by federal mediator William Usery broke down.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The next day, the owners approved a salary cap plan by a vote of 25–3, but agreed to delay implementing it so that another round of talks with the players could be held.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On December 23, with negotiations at a standstill, the owners unilaterally implemented a salary cap.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On January 4, 1995, five bills aimed at ending the baseball strike were introduced into Congress.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The next day, Fehr declared all 895 unsigned Major League players to be free agents in response to unilateral contract changes made by the owners.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On January 10, arbitrator Thomas Roberts awarded 11 players a total of almost $10 million as a result of collusion charges brought against the owners.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On January 26, both players and owners were ordered by President Bill Clinton to resume bargaining and reach an agreement by February 6.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Unfortunately, President Clinton's deadline came and went with no resolution of the strike.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Just five days earlier, the owners agreed to revoke the salary cap and return to the old agreement.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] After the deadline passed with no compromises, the use of replacement players for spring training and regular season games was approved by baseball's executive council on January 13.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Replacement players were guaranteed $5,000 for reporting to spring training and another $5,000 if they made the Opening Day roster.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 14, the players' union announced that it would not settle the strike if replacement players were used in regular season games, and if results were not voided.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Detroit Tigers manager Sparky Anderson was put on an involuntary leave of absence as he refused to manage replacement players.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] He retired soon after the 1995 season ended, disillusioned with the state of the sport.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Replacement players created major issues for two American League teams.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Toronto Blue Jays could not play games with replacement players or umpires in Ontario, due to labour code amendments passed by the Ontarian Government that prohibited replacement workers.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Manager Cito Gaston and his coaching staff were sent to work with minor league players, and the team announced that games featuring replacement workers would be played at their spring training facility in Dunedin, Florida.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Baltimore Orioles, owned by labor lawyer Peter Angelos, announced they would also not be using replacement players.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 20, the Orioles canceled the remainder of their spring training games.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 28, Maryland governor Parris Glendening signed a law barring teams playing at Camden Yards from using replacement players.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 24, Atlanta Braves replacement pitcher Dave Shotkoski was shot and killed near the team hotel in West Palm Beach, Florida.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Fellow replacement player Terry Blocker assisted police in locating the suspect, who was later convicted of second-degree murder.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 26, MLB announced that the 1995 season would be reduced from 162 games per team to 144 games per team as a result of the use of replacement players.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Following the end of the 1993 season, CBS Sports lost the rights to broadcast baseball games on television.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Production of nationally televised games was taken over by MLB itself, which sold the games as brokered programming to ABC and NBC as part of a joint venture that was referred to as The Baseball Network.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Originally, the idea was for ABC and NBC to share a slate of games aired in prime time during the week, with the two networks alternating coverage of the All-Star Game and World Series and splitting the Division and League Championship Series between them.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike, however, resulted in ABC losing out on two weeks of coverage and the World Series and NBC losing out on all of its allotted regular season games.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] MLB and the local NBC and ABC stations lost a combined $595 million in advertising revenue, and both networks announced that they would be opting out of the deal after the shortened 1995 season.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Both networks would share coverage of the World Series that year, with ABC airing the odd numbered games and NBC the even numbered games.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Fox became the new broadcast partner for MLB in 1996 and has remained as such since.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] NBC did elect to retain some broadcast rights; however, it continued to air the All-Star Game in even numbered years and retained its rights to air the World Series in odd numbered years until Fox gained exclusive rights to national MLB broadcasts in 2001.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 29, 1995, the players voted to return to work if a U.S.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] District Court judge supported the National Labor Relations Board's unfair labor practices complaint against the owners, which was filed on March 27.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] By a vote of 26–2, owners supported the use of replacement players.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Judge (and future Supreme Court Justice) Sonia Sotomayor of the U.S.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] District Court for the Southern District of New York issued a preliminary injunction against the owners on March 31.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On April 2, the day before the season was scheduled to start with the replacement players, the strike came to an official end at 232 days.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Judge Sotomayor's decision received support from a panel of the Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit, which denied the owners' request to stay the ruling.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] During the first days of the 1995 season, some fans remained irate at both players and owners.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Attendance at the games plummeted, as did television ratings, to a greater extent than during the last significant players' strike in 1981.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] While a total of 50,010,016 fans had attended the 1,600 MLB regular season games played in 1994, averaging 31,256 per game, a total of 50,416,880 fans attended the 2,016 games of the 1995 MLB regular season, for an average attendance of just 25,008 per game.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This represented a decline in average attendance of 20% from 1994 to 1995.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] A few of the fans who showed up demonstrated their frustration, and booed the players; the strike was seen as the worst work stoppage in sports history, leaving the game in crisis and some fans angry.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Writer Chuck Klosterman observed that during previous strikes, public anger was directed most fervently at players, but the 1994 strike attracted outrage at both players and owners in apparently equal measure.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The opening games were played with replacement umpires, the first time since Opening Day 1991 that replacement umpires were used.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On August 3, 1995, the Senate Judiciary Committee sent a bill calling for the partial repeal of baseball's antitrust exemption to the full Senate on a 9–8 vote.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In August, George Nicolau, baseball's arbitrator since 1986, was fired by the owners.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On September 29, a three-judge panel in New York voted unanimously to uphold the injunction that brought the end to the strike in April.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The owners had appealed the injunction issued on March 31, but the panel said the Players Relations Committee had illegally attempted to eliminate free agency and salary arbitration.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The affected players include Shane Spencer of the 1998, 1999, and 2000 New York Yankees; Damian Miller of the 2001 Arizona Diamondbacks; Brendan Donnelly of the 2002 Anaheim Angels; Kevin Millar and Brian Daubach of the 2004 Boston Red Sox; and Jamie Walker of the 2006 Detroit Tigers.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Arguably the largest impact was to the Montreal Expos.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike was considered to be the start of the franchise's downfall in Montreal, eventually leading MLB to relocate them to Washington, D.C., to become the current Washington Nationals.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Expos were one of the league's top teams, and had the best record in MLB, and were six games ahead of the Atlanta Braves in the NL East.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In 1995, they were forced to lower payroll and sell off their four highest-paid stars (Marquis Grissom, Ken Hill, Larry Walker, and John Wetteland) in the span of less than a week in spring training.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] With the strike negatively affecting its fan base, the Expos would never recover from the incident.
[src:american-league/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] After the 1994–95 strike, players' strikes became less common, although major professional sports leagues have seen lockouts amidst labor disputes between owners and players' unions.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] The **1998 Major League Baseball expansion** resulted in the establishment of Major League Baseball (MLB)'s 29th and 30th teams beginning play for the 1998 season.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] After initiating an expansion committee in March 1994, 27 groups representing nine cities submitted bids for the proposed expansion teams.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] After a yearlong process, on March 9, 1995, the league awarded the National League franchise to Phoenix and the American League franchise to Tampa Bay.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Arizona Diamondbacks and the Tampa Bay Devil Rays (currently the Tampa Bay Rays), subsequently began play for the 1998 season.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] With the successes of the Colorado Rockies and Florida Marlins following the 1993 expansion, Major League Baseball by 1994 was looking to expand again from 28 to 30 teams.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] On March 2, 1994, MLB created an expansion committee to evaluate the feasibility of expansion.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] Although both Phoenix and Tampa Bay were believed to be overwhelming favorites for the franchises, other cities were invited to bid for the proposed franchises.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] Coleman, Jr., and the president of the American League, Bobby Brown.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] By June, the league announced that all cities with interest in the proposed franchises should submit their intentions by June 24.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] By June 30, the committee released the nine communities that submitted information to MLB for the proposed franchises.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] Buffalo, Nashville, Northern Virginia, Orlando, Phoenix, Tampa Bay and Vancouver placed expansion requests.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] Other cities mentioned as potential expansion locations which did not officially submit an application to the league included Charlotte and Washington.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] After whittling down the field to four finalists (Northern Virginia, Orlando, Phoenix and Tampa Bay), MLB announced Phoenix and Tampa Bay as the two expansion franchises on March 9, 1995.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] Announced to begin play for the 1998 season, each ownership group paid a $130 million expansion fee to enter the league.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] The ownership groups paid $32 million in July 1995, $25 million in July 1996, $40 million in July 1997 and $33 million in November 1997.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] In addition, the two expansion teams gave away their rights to $5 million from baseball's central fund for each of the five years following expansion (1998–2002).
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] The adding of the 29th and 30th team caused the American League and the National League to have fifteen teams each.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] Because of the odd number of teams, only seven games could possibly be scheduled in each league on any given day.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] Thus, one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] This would have made it difficult for scheduling, in terms of travel days and the need to end the season before October.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] The 1998 expansion remains the most recent to be conducted in Major League Baseball.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] MLB would later reverse the imbalance created by the 1998 expansion when, following the sale of the Houston Astros, the new owners agreed to move their franchise to the American League before the 2013 season.
[src:american-league/1998-major-league-baseball-expansion] Following that transaction, MLB consequently altered its season structure so as to include interleague play throughout the regular season.
[src:american-league/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:american-league/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:american-league/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:american-league/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:american-league/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:american-league/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:american-league/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:american-league/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:american-league/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:american-league/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:american-league/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:american-league/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:american-league/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:american-league/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:american-league/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:american-league/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:american-league/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:american-league/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:american-league/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:american-league/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:american-league/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:american-league/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:american-league/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:american-league/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:american-league/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:american-league/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:american-league/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:american-league/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:american-league/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:american-league/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:american-league/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:american-league/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:american-league/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:american-league/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:american-league/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:american-league/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:american-league/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:american-league/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:american-league/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:american-league/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:american-league/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:american-league/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:american-league/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:american-league/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:american-league/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:american-league/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:american-league/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:american-league/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:american-league/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:american-league/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:american-league/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:american-league/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:american-league/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:american-league/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:american-league/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:american-league/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
